"{\"uid\": \"rappler.com-sports-boxing-taiwan-lin-yu-ting-wins-women-boxing-gold-amid-gender-row-paris-olympics-2024\", \"text\": \"  SUMMARY  This is AI generated summarization, which may have errors. For context, always refer to the full article.  CHAMPION. Boxer Lin Yu-ting of Taiwan celebrates winning against Julia Szeremeta of Poland in the final of the women's 57kg division in the 2024 Paris Olympics.  Pilar Olivares/REUTERS  PARIS, France - Lin\\u00a0Yu-ting, one of two boxers at the heart of a gender\\u00a0dispute\\u00a0in the Paris Games, made light work of Polish opponent Julia Szeremeta to claim\\u00a0the women's\\u00a0featherweight\\u00a0title on\\u00a0Saturday, August 10.  Lin\\u00a0and Algeria'sImane Khelif, who won gold in the welterweight category on Friday, have been in the spotlight as part of a gender dispute that has dominated headlines and been the subject of much discussion on social media platforms.  The 28-year-old\\u00a0Lin\\u00a0became Taiwan's first gold medalist in boxing, with the island having previously won only three bronze medals in the sport - two of which came at the Paris Olympics.  Lin\\u00a0and Khelif were disqualified by the International Boxing Association (IBA) from the 2023 World Championships in New Delhi, with the body saying in a shambolic\\u00a0press conference\\u00a0at the Paris Games that\\u00a0a gender test had ruled them ineligible.  The two boxers are competing\\u00a0in the Olympics after the International Olympic Committee (IOC) stripped the IBA of its status as the sport's governing body in 2023 and took control of organizing the boxing in Paris.  The IOC has rejected the results of the IBA-ordered tests as arbitrary and illegitimate, saying there was no reason to conduct them.  At these Games, the IOC is using boxing eligibility rules that were applied at the 2016 and 2021 Olympics, which do not include gender testing.  In a post on X ahead of\\u00a0Lin's bout, Taiwan President Lai Ching-te said the boxer was carrying \\\"the strength of a nation.\\\"  \\\"She has faced adversity and senseless attacks from beyond the ring with incredible grace and unwavering courage. We are cheering her on to the finish,\\\" Lai added.  Using her jab to keep\\u00a0Szeremeta\\u00a0at bay,\\u00a0Lin\\u00a0landed a couple of right hooks as\\u00a0the Pole\\u00a0was looking to break the distance.  Szeremeta\\u00a0was full of good intentions but lacked speed and accuracy, exposing herself to a potential counter blow.  Lin\\u00a0also had\\u00a0more speed in a one-sided bout that forced Szeremeta to go all in\\u00a0during the\\u00a0last round, and the Taiwanese was just content to dodge the attacks.  Nesthy Petecioof the Philippines and Turkey's Esra Yildiz were awarded bronze.- Rappler.com  How does this make you feel?  follow us          \"}"